    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c85517789a41171dc8110723335658fe?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 3526396,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2947357,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2947357/maphongba008",
                "reputation": 2393,
                "display_name": "maphongba008",
                "accept_rate": 65
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 12,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1551348707,
            "creation_date": 1551348707,
            "body": "<p>I finally found the answer, because the Process I start is different with the process of the terminal, so can't access /usr/local/bin, have to add <code>-l<\/code> to run the command as logged in user.\n<code>Runtime.getRuntime().exec(new String[]{\"bash\", \"-l\", \"-c\", cmd}, null, new File(f))<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 54923150,
            "question_id": 54742540
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/69a5f131415868fa8444381eaaa16ca5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 12321033,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 8990329,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8990329/some-name",
                "reputation": 9750,
                "display_name": "Some Name",
                "accept_rate": 70
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1550477129,
            "creation_date": 1550476704,
            "body": "<p>As <code>error<\/code> code 2 suggests you specified a path incorrectly. The error code corresponds to POSIX <code>ENOENT<\/code> and \"No such file or directory\" its <code>char * strerror(int errno)<\/code> representation.<\/p>\n\n<p>To troubleshoot the problem by yourself you can read the manual page <a href=\"http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/execve.2.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/execve.2.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The relevant section is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>ENOENT <\/p>\n  \n  <p>The file filename or a script or ELF interpreter does not \n  exist, or a shared library needed for the file or interpreter \n  cannot be found.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>To see with which particula path your process is strarted run java witj <code>strace -f<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 54742688,
            "question_id": 54742540,
            "last_edit_date": 1550477129
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fc734cbb2943ede96ba14a185023f829?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 470637,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 877935,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/877935/marco-antonio-monroy-conde",
                "reputation": 31,
                "display_name": "Marco Antonio Monroy Conde"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1583388158,
            "creation_date": 1583388158,
            "body": "<p>In my case, I was using an ANT script that at some point called javac task with a fork=true attribute. Inspired by maphongba008 answer I deleted that fork, and so I stopped getting this same error.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 60539052,
            "question_id": 54742540
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/wzMFz.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 25223771,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 19059901,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/19059901/heisenbug",
                "reputation": 511,
                "display_name": "Heisenbug"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1724075428,
            "creation_date": 1724075428,
            "body": "<p>I too faced for the same &quot;Process p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);&quot;.<\/p>\n<p>Other solutions didn't worked as everything was correct and as expected.<\/p>\n<p>I was using the downloaded JDK as Installed JRE's in eclipse and facing error.<\/p>\n<p>Then I tried to search the JDK which is installed by sudo apt which resides in<\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>/usr/lib/jvm/java-11-openjdk-amd64<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>Upon selecting this JDK, everything started working fine.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/kEZfSeMb.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/kEZfSeMb.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\" /><\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 78888227,
            "question_id": 54742540
